      Who controls a company?
   =20
 =20
Well, see, there are formalities. If you own 97% of the voting stock of a p=
ublic company then in some rough general sense you control it. You get to v=
ote for directors each year, and the directors you vote for will be elected=
. But you normally won=E2=80=99t pick a board consisting of yourself and yo=
ur dog; you=E2=80=99ll vote for a reasonably professional board consisting =
of several different people chosen through some defensible process. So on=
=C2=A0a controversial matter you might find that the rest of the board disa=
grees with you, you=E2=80=99re outvoted, and the company does the thing you=
 don=E2=80=99t want.If you feel strongly about the matter, owning 97% of th=
e stock, you can fire the rest of the board and replace them with (hopefull=
y) more pliable allies. But, at a public company, you can=E2=80=99t necessa=
rily do that=C2=A0today. The actual formalities will depend on the company=
=E2=80=99s corporate documents, and there is a range of how quickly you can=
 act. Perhaps you will need to follow certain procedures to vote your share=
s =E2=80=9Cby written consent=E2=80=9D and kick out the board. Perhaps you =
will need to call a =E2=80=9Cshareholder meeting=E2=80=9D and give weeks of=
 notice before voting your shares to kick out the board.[1] Perhaps you wil=
l need to wait for the board =E2=80=94=C2=A0whom you=E2=80=99re mad at =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0to call the=C2=A0annual=C2=A0shareholder meeting before you can=
 vote them out, which could be months away. Meanwhile the company is doing =
the thing you didn=E2=80=99t want it to do and you are just stuck outside, =
plotting your revenge.Perhaps, as you plot your revenge, the board will be =
plotting to take your shares away from you. This is a pretty advanced move =
and probably won=E2=80=99t work, but CBS Corp.=E2=80=99s directors  did try=
 it in 2018=C2=A0when they had a disagreement with their controlling shareh=
older. (It did not work.) =E2=80=9CControl=E2=80=9D is not a simple matter.=
 You have some powers, and the board has some powers, and you will each mak=
e active moves to grab territory from the other.It gets worse. Instead of o=
ne person owning 97% of the voting shares, you could have a family owning 9=
7% of the voting shares. The shares could be in a trust, to benefit the who=
le family. One advantage of putting the shares in a trust might be to conce=
ntrate the voting power and make all 97% of the shares vote the same way. S=
o instead of each family member owning some shares and voting however they =
like, possibly against each other, the trustees =E2=80=94=C2=A0family membe=
rs or outside advisers or a mix =E2=80=94=C2=A0get together, vote on how to=
 vote the shares, and then all of the shares are voted=C2=A0in an insurmoun=
table bloc.Here too there will be formalities. If some of the family member=
s are unhappy with the trustees=E2=80=99 decisions they may be able to fire=
 them and replace them with different trustees (e.g. themselves), or they m=
ay not, or they may be able to with a supermajority and a notice period and=
 proper procedures. In general a private family trust can have weirder, mor=
e convoluted, less democratic procedures than a public company.And the form=
alities can be=C2=A0different, and can=C2=A0lead to different results. And =
so you can have a situation where a=C2=A0family controls a public company a=
nd the family members sit on the company=E2=80=99s board of directors, own =
its voting shares, and sit on the committee of the trust that votes the sha=
res, but the exact mechanics of how they sit on those boards are different =
and produce different results.=C2=A0You could have a situation where the ma=
jority of the family wants Thing 1, but the trustees (including family memb=
ers) in charge of the family trust vote the family=E2=80=99s shares for Thi=
ng 2, but the board of directors=C2=A0 of the company (again including fami=
ly members) chooses Thing 3. And then the family members=C2=A0will all be r=
eally mad at each other. And because they are all wealthy heirs, they will =
have a lot of time and money to devote to being amusingly mean to each othe=
r.=C2=A0Anyway here=E2=80=99s a great=C2=A0story out of Canada:There has pe=
rhaps never been a boardroom fight in Canadian financial history quite like=
 the one that=E2=80=99s raging inside Rogers Communications Inc.Pitting son=
 against mother and brother against sisters, it=E2=80=99s pulled out into b=
road daylight a nasty, internecine feud that had been brewing behind closed=
 doors ever since the patriarch of the family, Ted Rogers, died in 2008.Aft=
er a week of attacks and counterattacks, which came like rapid fire one aft=
er the other, Edward Rogers -- Ted=E2=80=99s only son -- appears to have th=
e upper hand against his mother and sisters in the struggle for control of =
Canada=E2=80=99s biggest wireless company. =C2=A0What=E2=80=99s unclear is =
whether he can hold onto that power -- both sides claimed Sunday that their=
 slate of board directors was in charge -- and, more importantly, whether w=
hoever ends up on top can turn around a sputtering business and breathe lif=
e into a stock that has badly lagged behind rivals since Ted=E2=80=99s pass=
ing.=C2=A0Edward Rogers was the leading family member at the company, servi=
ng as chairman both of the company=E2=80=99s board of directors and of =E2=
=80=9Cthe Rogers Control Trust, the private entity that controls about 97% =
of the voting shares at Rogers Communications.=E2=80=9D But last week he lo=
st control of the company=E2=80=99s board, when his sisters and mother vote=
d against him for trying to fire the CEO:The power struggle between Edward =
Rogers, his family members and company executives has been going on for yea=
rs. But things really began to boil over when he hatched a plan to oust Chi=
ef Executive Officer Joe Natale and a number other senior executives and pr=
omote Chief Financial Officer Tony Staffieri to the top job.=C2=A0Edward=E2=
=80=99s sisters -- Melinda Rogers-Hixon and Martha Rogers -- and mother -- =
Loretta Rogers, Ted=E2=80=99s widow -- joined other directors in siding wit=
h Natale and blocking the change. They also took unprecedented measures to =
limit Edward=E2=80=99s authority, including removing him as chairman on Oct=
. 21.=C2=A0In a fitting twist for such a wild affair, Staffieri accidentall=
y revealed the coup plot to Natale by pocket-dialing the CEO while he was d=
iscussing it with someone else, according to a person with knowledge of the=
 incident, which was reported first by the Globe and Mail.Oops. So the boar=
d =E2=80=94=C2=A0including his sisters and mother =E2=80=94=C2=A0fired Edwa=
rd Rogers as chairman of the board of the company.Then his mother and siste=
rs tried to fire him as chairman of the trust, but the trust board and the =
company board are different and have different rules, and=C2=A0that did=C2=
=A0not=C2=A0work:Edward Rogers defeated an effort to limit his voting power=
 at Rogers Communications Inc., paving the way for his extraordinary attemp=
t to replace five directors on the company=E2=80=99s board with his allies.=
=C2=A0During a meeting of the Rogers Control Trust, Edward Rogers=E2=80=99 =
mother, two of his sisters and Toronto Mayor John Tory tried to pass a meas=
ure that would have restricted his ability to use shares from the trust to =
vote his directors onto the public company=E2=80=99s board, according to pe=
ople familiar with the matter.It needed support of seven of 10 people on th=
e trust=E2=80=99s advisory committee, but got only four, the people said, a=
sking not to be identified because the matter is private. The trust is the =
private entity that controls Rogers Communications, Canada=E2=80=99s larges=
t cable and wireless firm.So now he controls the corporate shares but they =
control the corporate board. But since he controls the shares he can fire t=
he board. So he did. Or did he?The escalating crisis at Rogers Communicatio=
ns Inc. has taken another extraordinary twist, with two different men claim=
ing they are chairman and two factions of the Rogers family each saying the=
