10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Who controls a company?</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, see, there are formalities. If y=
ou own 97% of the voting stock of a public company then in some rough gener=
al sense you control it. You get to vote for directors each year, and the d=
irectors you vote for will be elected. But you normally won=E2=80=99t pick =
a board consisting of yourself and your dog; you=E2=80=99ll vote for a reas=
onably professional board consisting of several different people chosen thr=
ough some defensible process. So on=C2=A0a controversial matter you might f=
ind that the rest of the board disagrees with you, you=E2=80=99re outvoted,=
 and the company does the thing you don=E2=80=99t want.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">If you feel strongly about the matter, owning 97% of the stock=
, you can fire the rest of the board and replace them with (hopefully) more=
 pliable allies. But, at a public company, you can=E2=80=99t necessarily do=
 that=C2=A0<em>today</em>. The actual formalities will depend on the compan=
y=E2=80=99s corporate documents, and there is a range of how quickly you ca=
n act. Perhaps you will need to follow certain procedures to vote your shar=
es =E2=80=9Cby written consent=E2=80=9D and kick out the board. Perhaps you=
 will need to call a =E2=80=9Cshareholder meeting=E2=80=9D and give weeks o=
f notice before voting your shares to kick out the board.[1] Perhaps you wi=
ll need to wait for the board =E2=80=94=C2=A0whom you=E2=80=99re mad at =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0to call the=C2=A0<em>annual=C2=A0</em>shareholder meeting befor=
e you can vote them out, which could be months away. Meanwhile the company =
is doing the thing you didn=E2=80=99t want it to do and you are just stuck =
outside, plotting your revenge.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Perhaps, as=
 you plot your revenge, the board will be plotting to <em>take your shares =
away from you</em>. This is a pretty advanced move and probably won=E2=80=
=99t work, but CBS Corp.=E2=80=99s directors <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/25459351.257692/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNv=
bS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDUtMTUvY2JzLXdhbnRzLXRvLWdldC1yaWQtb2YtYS1=
zaGFyZWhvbGRlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDI1MjFfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJn=
V0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMTEwMjUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c=
3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa0ffb297" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> did try it</a> in 2018=
=C2=A0when they had a disagreement with their controlling shareholder. (It =
did not work.) =E2=80=9CControl=E2=80=9D is not a simple matter. You have s=
ome powers, and the board has some powers, and you will each make active mo=
ves to grab territory from the other.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It ge=
ts worse. Instead of one person owning 97% of the voting shares, you could =
have a family owning 97% of the voting shares. The shares could be in a tru=
st, to benefit the whole family. One advantage of putting the shares in a t=
rust might be to concentrate the voting power and make all 97% of the share=
s vote the same way. So instead of each family member owning some shares an=
d voting however they like, possibly against each other, the trustees =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0family members or outside advisers or a mix =E2=80=94=C2=A0get =
together, vote on how to vote the shares, and then all of the shares are vo=
ted=C2=A0in an insurmountable bloc.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here to=
o there will be formalities. If some of the family members are unhappy with=
 the trustees=E2=80=99 decisions they may be able to fire them and replace =
them with different trustees (e.g. themselves), or they may not, or they ma=
y be able to with a supermajority and a notice period and proper procedures=
. In general a private family trust can have weirder, more convoluted, less=
 democratic procedures than a public company.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">And the formalities can be=C2=A0<em>different</em>, and can=C2=A0lead to=
 different<em> </em>results. And so you can have a situation where a=C2=A0f=
amily controls a public company and the family members sit on the company=
=E2=80=99s board of directors, own its voting shares, and sit on the commit=
tee of the trust that votes the shares, but the exact mechanics of how they=
 sit on those boards are different and produce different results.=C2=A0You =
could have a situation where the majority of the family wants Thing 1, but =
the trustees (including family members) in charge of the family trust vote =
the family=E2=80=99s shares for Thing 2, but the board of directors=C2=A0 o=
f the company (again including family members) chooses Thing 3. And then th=
e family members=C2=A0will all be really mad at each other. And because the=
y are all wealthy heirs, they will have a lot of time and money to devote t=
o being amusingly mean to each other.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Anyway here=E2=80=99s a great=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/25459351.257692/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMjQvcm9nZXJzLWJvYXJkcm9vbS1icmF3bC1waXR0aW5nLXNvbi12=
cy1tb3RoZXItd2FzLXllYXJzLWluLW1ha2luZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDI1MjFfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ=
1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMTEwMjUmdX=
RtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB084f0de3" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
story out of Canada</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There =
has perhaps never been a boardroom fight in Canadian financial history quit=
e like the one that=E2=80=99s raging inside Rogers Communications Inc.</p><=
p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pitting son against mother and brother against =
sisters, it=E2=80=99s pulled out into broad daylight a nasty, internecine f=
eud that had been brewing behind closed doors ever since the patriarch of t=
he family, Ted Rogers, died in 2008.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After =
a week of attacks and counterattacks, which came like rapid fire one after =
the other, Edward Rogers -- Ted=E2=80=99s only son -- appears to have the u=
pper hand against his mother and sisters in the struggle for control of Can=
ada=E2=80=99s biggest wireless company. =C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">What=E2=80=99s unclear is whether he can hold onto that power -- both s=
ides claimed Sunday that their slate of board directors was in charge -- an=
d, more importantly, whether whoever ends up on top can turn around a sputt=
ering business and breathe life into a stock that has badly lagged behind r=
ivals since Ted=E2=80=99s passing.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Edward Rogers was the leading family member at the company, serv=
ing as chairman both of the company=E2=80=99s board of directors and of =E2=
=80=9Cthe Rogers Control Trust, the private entity that controls about 97% =
of the voting shares at Rogers Communications.=E2=80=9D But last week he lo=
st control of the company=E2=80=99s board, when his sisters and mother vote=
d against him for trying to fire the CEO:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">The power struggle between Edward Rogers, his family members and=
 company executives has been going on for years. But things really began to=
 boil over when he hatched a plan to oust Chief Executive Officer Joe Natal=
e and a number other senior executives and promote Chief Financial Officer =
Tony Staffieri to the top job.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Edward=
=E2=80=99s sisters -- Melinda Rogers-Hixon and Martha Rogers -- and mother =
-- Loretta Rogers, Ted=E2=80=99s widow -- joined other directors in siding =
with Natale and blocking the change. They also took unprecedented measures =
to limit Edward=E2=80=99s authority, including removing him as chairman on =
Oct. 21.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a fitting twist for such =
a wild affair, Staffieri accidentally revealed the coup plot to Natale by p=
ocket-dialing the CEO while he was discussing it with someone else, accordi=
ng to a person with knowledge of the incident, which was reported first by =
the Globe and Mail.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oops. So t=
he board =E2=80=94=C2=A0including his sisters and mother =E2=80=94=C2=A0fir=
ed Edward Rogers as chairman of the board of the company.</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Then his mother and sisters tried to fire him as chairman of=
 the trust, but the trust board and the company board are different and hav=
e different rules, and=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
com/click/25459351.257692/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljb=
GVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMjIvZWR3YXJkLXJvZ2Vycy1kZWZlYXRzLWZhbWlseS1zLWF0dGVtcHQtdG8t=
bGltaXQtaGlzLXZvdGluZy1wb3dlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDI1MjFfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWV=
kaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMTEwMjUmdXRtX2NhbX=
BhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1f5e327f" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">that did=
=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>work</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Edward Rogers defeated an effort to limit his voting power at Rogers Com=
munications Inc., paving the way for his extraordinary attempt to replace f=
ive directors on the company=E2=80=99s board with his allies.=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During a meeting of the Rogers Control Trust, Edwa=
rd Rogers=E2=80=99 mother, two of his sisters and Toronto Mayor John Tory t=
ried to pass a measure that would have restricted his ability to use shares=
 from the trust to vote his directors onto the public company=E2=80=99s boa=
rd, according to people familiar with the matter.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">It needed support of seven of 10 people on the trust=E2=80=99s advis=
ory committee, but got only four, the people said, asking not to be identif=
ied because the matter is private. The trust is the private entity that con=
trols Rogers Communications, Canada=E2=80=99s largest cable and wireless fi=
rm.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So now he controls the cor=
porate shares but they control the corporate board. But since he controls t=
he shares he can fire the board. So he did. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/25459351.257692/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
S9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTAtMjQvcm9nZXJzLWZhbWlseS1mZXVkLWNvbnRpbnVlcy1h=
aGVhZC1vZi1tZWV0aW5nLW9mLW5ldy1ib2FyZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDI1MjFfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ=
1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMTEwMjUmdX=
RtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4606ec23" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
Or did he</a>?</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The escalating c=
risis at Rogers Communications Inc. has taken another extraordinary twist, =
with two different men claiming they are chairman and two factions of the R=
ogers family each saying they have control of the board.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">Edward Rogers was named chairman at a meeting in Toronto on S=
unday night, according to a statement by a group that says it represents th=
e =E2=80=9Creconstituted board=E2=80=9D with five new members.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the company says that meeting was not valid, the 1=
4-member board hasn=E2=80=99t changed at all and John MacDonald remains the=
 chairman. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Edward Rogers] believes he=
=E2=80=99s able to replace directors immediately through a resolution rathe=
r than a traditional vote at a shareholder meeting.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Directors can removed by an ordinary resolution, according t=
o the articles of incorporation posted on Rogers Communications=E2=80=99 we=
bsite. The articles also state that the vacancy created may be filled at th=
e same meeting.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"htt=
